Hi,
I found that some init.d scripts have commands on the same line as case=20
statement. For exemple, /etc/init.d/cron on my system, has:

[...]
start)	log_daemon_msg "Starting periodic command scheduler" "crond"
[...]
stop)	log_daemon_msg "Stopping periodic command scheduler" "crond"
[...]
restart) log_daemon_msg "Restarting periodic command scheduler" "crond"=20
[...]

_init_d currently does not match such constructions: It uses ':#' and=20
therefore only matches case statements if there is nothing else on the line=
=2E=20
If using '##' it can match case statements even if there are other things o=
n=20
the line.

I couldn't think of any drawback, so here is a patch:

arno

--- _init_d.old	2007-12-06 15:24:02.000000000 +0100
+++ _init_d	2007-12-06 15:25:24.000000000 +0100
@@ -15,7 +15,7 @@
 what=3D'(st(art|op|atus)|(force-|)re(start|load)|debug_(up|down)|dump(|_st=
ats)|add|delete|clean|list)'
=20
 read -u0 -k2 magic < $script && [[ $magic =3D '#!' ]] &&
-    cmds=3D( ${${(j:|:s:|:)${(M)${(f)"$(< $script)"}:#[[:blank:]]#(\'|)${~=
what}([[:blank:]]#\|[[:blank:]]#${~what})#(\'|)\)}}//[^-a-z_]} )
+    cmds=3D( ${${(j:|:s:|:)${(M)${(f)"$(< $script)"}##[[:blank:]]#(\'|)${~=
what}([[:blank:]]#\|[[:blank:]]#${~what})#(\'|)\)}}//[^-a-z_]} )
=20
 # This would be the pattern to use every line of the form <space>foo).
 # Some people say this might match too many lines...

--PNTmBPCT7hxwcZjr
